03714nam a22004935i 9780228000624DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20192019xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280006247 a10.1515/97802280006242doi  a(DE-B1597)655455  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aRA780b.W37 2019 7aSOC0050002bisacsh04a613/.42231 aWard, Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Clean Body :bA Modern History /cPeter Ward. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource :b12 b&w images, 4 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tBeginnings -- tContexts -- tCleanliness as Tradition -- tBefore the Deluge -- tCleanliness as Habit -- tPublic Places, Private Spaces -- tClothes and Their Cleaning -- tThe Soap Trade and the New Hygiene -- tThe Educators -- tCleanliness as Commodity -- tBathrooms and Bathing -- tThe Laundry Revolution -- tCleanliness and the Beauty Business -- tMaking the Modern Clean Body -- tAcknowledgments -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow often did our ancestors bathe? How often did they wash their clothes and change them? What did they understand cleanliness to be? Why have our hygienic habits changed so dramatically over time? In short, how have we come to be so clean? The Clean Body explores one of the most fundamental and pervasive cultural changes in Western history since the seventeenth century: the personal hygiene revolution. In the age of Louis XIV bathing was rare and hygiene was mainly a matter of wearing clean underclothes. By the late twentieth century frequent - often daily - bathing had become the norm and wearing freshly laundered clothing the general practice. Cleanliness, once simply a requirement for good health, became an essential element of beauty. Beneath this transformation lay a sea change in understandings, motives, ideologies, technologies, and practices, all of which shaped popular habits over time. Peter Ward explains that what began as an urban bourgeois phenomenon in the later eighteenth century became a universal condition by the end of the twentieth, touching young and old, rich and poor, city dwellers and country residents alike. Based on a wealth of sources in English, French, German, and Italian, The Clean Body surveys the great hygienic transformation that took place across Europe and North America over the course of four centuries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBathing customszWestern countriesxHistory. 0aHealth attitudes. 0aHygienezWestern countriesxHistory. 0aLaundryzWestern countriesxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Customs & Traditions.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978022800062440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228000624423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228000624/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles